text:
Code github: https://github.com/krishnaik06/Gen-AI...
In the video we will see how we will be implementing end to end GENAI App using Deepseek R1 with Langchain And Ollama.
Released in January 2025, this model is based on DeepSeek-V3 and is focused on advanced reasoning tasks directly competing with OpenAI's o1 model in performance, while maintaining a significantly lower cost structure. Like DeepSeek-V3, the model has 671 billion parameters with a context length of 128,000

analysis.summary: The video is a tutorial about developing easy end-to-end generative AI applications using the DeepSeek R1 model. The presenter integrates this model using Ollama locally, avoiding sending data to China. He explores chat.deepseek.com, mentioning server issues due to high traffic and his partial replacement of ChatGPT with DeepSeek. The tutorial will demonstrate creating a generative AI app for chatting with memory, remembering chat history, and implementing it using LangChain. He chooses not to use the DeepSeek API due to data privacy concerns and cost per million tokens. He downloads the DeepSeek R1 model with Ollama, emphasizing the availability of models with varying billion parameters. He opens his command prompt and then shares his VS Code page.

qa.question: What is the purpose of the video tutorial?
qa.answer: The tutorial shows how to develop generative AI applications using DeepSeek R1 with Ollama.
qa.context: The video is a tutorial about developing easy end-to-end generative AI applications using the DeepSeek R1 model.

qa.question: Why does the presenter integrate the DeepSeek model locally?
qa.answer: He integrates it locally to avoid sending data to China and to avoid cost per million tokens.

qa.answer: The presenter plans to use LangChain as the framework.

qa.answer: It allows the presenter to run the model locally and provides various options for model implementation.
